  "text": "We have implemented and tested multiresolution priority queues to improve the performance of Bro, an event-driven application which enables deep network analytics [CITATION_1] . Bro uses a standard priority queue implemented as a binary heap to manage the system's timers. While binary heaps are excellent implementations of priority queues, we find that when dealing with very high speed traffic (e.g., at rates of 10Gbps), they become a system bottleneck. This is illustrated in Fig. 3, which shows a call As shown, the function PriorityQueue::BubbleDown takes the top spot with a cost of 6.5% of the total processing cost. This function implements the standard bubble down operation (sometimes also know as heapify [CITATION_2] ) part of the binary heap based implementation of a priority queue. Specifically, Bro uses this method every time it needs to fetch the next element from the queue of timers.",
